    <p>
        Implicit solutions can be frustrating because neither the graph of the equation nor an interval over which a solution satisfying <m>y(0)=0</m> is defined is apparent.
        The problem of “seeing” what an implicit solution looks like can sometimes be overcome using technology.
    </p>

    <p>
        <alert>Recall</alert>: For a function of two variables <m>z=G(x,y)</m>, the <em>two-dimensional</em> curves defined by <m>G(x,y)=c</m>, where <m>c</m> is a constant, are called the <em>level curves</em> of the function.
    </p>

