    <p>
        <alert>Homework Exercises</alert>
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Solve the following differential equations using separation of variables.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>dy-(y-4)^{2}dx=0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>e^{x}y\dfrac{dy}{dx}=e^{-y}+e^{-7x-y}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\left(\dfrac{2y+5}{6x+7}\right)^{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dN}{dt}+N=Nte^{t+5}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                Find an explicit solution of the following initial-value problem.
                <me>
                    \dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{y^2-1}{x^2-1}, \hspace{.7cm}y(9)=9
                </me>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                Find an explicit solution of the following initial-value problem.
                <me>
                    (1+x^{4})dy+x(1+4y^{2})dx=0, \hspace{.7cm}y(1)=0
                </me>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
        <alert>Additional Exercises</alert>
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Solve the following differential equations using separation of variables.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=x(y^{2}+9)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(xy^{2}+x)dx +e^{x}dy=0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=y^{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{2}{x(y^3+1)}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                Find an explicit solution of the following initial-value problem.
                <me>
                    e^{x} dx - y dy = 0, \hspace{.7cm}y(0)=-1
                </me>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
        <alert>Selected Answers</alert>
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>y=4-\dfrac{1}{C+x}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{e^{-8x}}{8}+e^{-x}+e^{y}y-e^{y}=C</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{3}{2y+5}=C+\dfrac{1}{6x+7}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>N(t)=Ce^{te^{t+5}-t-e^{t+5}}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y=x</m>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y=\dfrac{1-x^2}{2(x^2+1)}</m> (<em>Hints:</em> (1) When you go to integrate the side with <m>y</m>, do a <m>u</m>-substitution with <m>y=\frac{1}{2}u</m>. This will help you get a constant of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> in front to help with cancellations later on when you will need: (2) to use the fact that <m>\tan^{-1}(a)+\tan^{-1}(b)=\tan^{-1}\left(\dfrac{a+b}{1-ab}\right)</m> if <m>ab&#x3C;1</m>. You do not need to show that <m>ab&#x3C;1</m> for this particular problem, but it would only be a few steps to verify that we satisfy this condition.)
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>y=3\tan (\frac{3}{2}x^{2}+C)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>y=\tan(xe^{-x}+e^{-x}+C)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>y=-\dfrac{1}{x+C}</m> and <m>y=0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{y^4}{4}+y-2\ln |x| = C</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y=-\sqrt{2e^{x}-1}</m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

